\(~~~~\)The first example consists of a comparison between estimates obtained from the PH partial ML results from , which is the classic regression model, and the proposed BP based PH modeling discussed in previous sections, either using already available or routines and interface to . In the second example, the assumption of proportional risks is violated thus a comparison between semiparametric PO model estimates were also done. The results obtained by maximizing the modified partial likelihood implemented in were compared to the proposed BP modeling available at the package.

\(~~~~\)For instance, consider reports on male larynx-cancer patients diagnosed during 1970s at a hospital in the Netherlands , the data is available in Appendix A (Table ). In addition, also consider the trials conducted by the United States veterans administration on advanced lung-cancer patients from differential effects of therapy on tumour cell patients; Table Appendix A shows the dataset. In order to investigate the proposed Bernstein polynomial regression, the Relative Difference (RD) is defined by RD \(=(\hat \beta_c - \hat\beta_r)/\mid\hat \beta_r \mid\), where \(\hat\beta_r\) is the estimate of an equivalent reference model already implemented in and \(\hat\beta_c\) is the estimate of the coefficient in the model being evaluated. At the end of this section, the guidelines on how to fit these data using in are outlined.

1 Laryngeal Cancer Data

The Proportional Hazards model was fitted on data from 90 male patients diagnosed with laryngeal cancer to test whether same age patients survival differ in distinct stages. In accordance with Osman and Ghosh (2012), the BP degree is set to be \(m = \sqrt{90} \approx 10\) and \(\tau = 10.7\) is the largest time observed. Following the settings assumed by Klein and Moeschberger (2006), the model covariates are age of the patient and indicators of stage II, III and IV. Hypothetically, zero aged patients in stage I refer to baseline group such that \(h(t \mid \mathbf{0})=h_0(t)\). The spsurv::spbp function is used to show the results according to ML and Bayesian inferential approaches. This data is provided in KMsurv package.

## Data
library(KMsurv)
data("larynx")

## Fit
library(spsurv)
## Loading required package: survival
## Loading required package: loo
## This is loo version 2.1.0.

## Loading required package: coda
## Loading required package: MASS
fitmle <- spsurv::spbp(Surv(time, delta) ~ age + factor(stage), data = larynx)

1.1 An alternative approach

An alternative approach to MLE is to attribute priors to the interest quantities in order to draw conclusions from the posterior densities obtained. All MCMC calculations are based on the state-of-art probabilistic software Stan. Again, using spbp function, it is possible to fit survival data, just switch to bayesian just using approach = "bayes".

fitbe <- spbp(Surv(time, delta) ~age + factor(stage),
               approach = "bayes", data = larynx)

1.2 Scaling the feature variables

It may occur non satisfactory results due to the overflow in the argument of the exponential function of the survival models (PH, PO or AFT). An efficient way to solve this problem is to reescale the variables. However, this alternative results in important changes to the inference procedure (explained in the last section).

 fitbe <- spbp(Surv(time, delta) ~ age + factor(stage),
               approach = "bayes", scale = T, data = larynx)

2 Rescaling variables

For instance, suppose there are two observed feature variables \(x_1\) and \(x_2\), such that an eventual rescaling (centering and scaling) gives us \(x^*_1 = \frac{x_1 - \bar x_1}{s}\) and \(x^*_2 = \frac{x_2 - \bar x_2}{s}\), in which \(\bar x = \sum \limits_{i = 1}^n \frac{x_i}{n}\) and \(s = \sqrt{ \sum \limits_{i = 1}^n\frac{ (x_i- \bar x)^2}{n-1}}\).

How these new variables \(x^*_1\) and \(x^*_2\) are interpreted from the inferencial point of view?

The techniques used in this package depends on a fully specified likelihood in terms of the hazard and survivor functions. Thus, it is enough to note what happens to these quantities in each of the modelling propositions when the feature variables are scaled.
